	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tomaitheous</b> [ Sun Aug 28, 2011 4:47 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: More slowdown with 60Hz modded Mega Drive, PAL SNES?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Amano_Jyaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Hello,<br /><br />I have a 60Hz modded Mega Drive and PAL SNES. Since the cpu clock speeds of the PAL Mega Drive and the PAL SNES are slightly lower than their NTSC counterparts, I was wondering if this will result in more (noticeably) slowdown when running US/JAP Games in 60Hz mode in contrast to running them on a Genesis or US SNES.</div>
<br />
<br /> If the cpu clock was <em>not</em> modified in anyway for these mods, then yes. There's a greater chance of slowdown VS a standard NTSC console. I mean, it's the very fact that you have less total cpu clock cycles per frame than a normal NTSC machine. But the keyword is chance. Whether it's a noticeable amount (in occurrance) or not, I couldn't say. Otherwise if the cpu speed matches that of NTSC model, then I don't see how there could be a difference.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


